's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. If not simply an invention, it may have been devised as a feminine equivalent of   Alan   (of which it is an anagram), or a shortened form of   Alana .  It seems to have been first used by the American film actress  Lana Turner  (  1920–1995 ), whose original name was  Julia ."]}]},{"name":"Fulk","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. The name was originally a short form of various compound names containing the word <i>volk</i> ‘people, tribe’ (compare modern English <i>folk</i>). It has gradually died out of general use, but is still used in certain families, in particular the Grevilles. Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke, was a leading figure at the court of Elizabeth I.  See also  Greville ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fulke","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. The name was originally a short form of various compound names containing the word <i>volk</i> ‘people, tribe’ (compare modern English <i>folk</i>). It has gradually died out of general use, but is still used in certain families, in particular the Grevilles. Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke, was a leading figure at the court of Elizabeth I.  See also  Greville ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":2,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":22,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":32,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705185,"age":42,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Fulk de Somery was born about 1064, in England. She had at least 2 sons with Fulk de Paynel."},"et":{"abt 1064–":"umbes 1064–Surnud","1060–1135":"1060–1135","1100–1125":"1100–1125","1100–1161":"1100–1161","1064–Female":"1064–Surnud","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","abt 1064":"umbes 1064","1086":"1086","1064":"1064","1096":"1096","1161":"1161","about 1100":"umbes 1100","1060":"1060","Dudley, Midlands, Leicestershire, England":"Midlands, Leicestershire, England","Dudley, Worcestershire, England":"Dudley, Worcestershire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"abt 1064–":"noin 1064–Kuollut","1060–1135":"1060–11